DAE`09-3 OrigID: A. jocassee. Larva.

Dave Etnier: " I relooked at the 7 Agapetus jocassee you bar-coded. The two in UT 1.1148, 10SMRTR1-035 and -036, both males, are jocassee, as are the three males from UT 1.1147 (-030, -031, -032); both -033 and -034 are larvae, and they could certainly be larvae of A. iridis. We have one lot of iridis from near there, same county, and the suggestion is that iridis emerges later than jocassee. We have taken the two species together, so it seems quite probable that they are actually iridis. The larvae of the two species are very similar. "-Oct 22, 2010.

notes:
DAE`09-4

Dave Etnier: " I relooked at the 7 Agapetus jocassee you bar-coded. The two in UT 1.1148, 10SMRTR1-035 and -036, both males, are jocassee, as are the three males from UT 1.1147 (-030, -031, -032); both -033 and -034 are larvae, and they could certainly be larvae of A. iridis. We have one lot of iridis from near there, same county, and the suggestion is that iridis emerges later than jocassee. We have taken the two species together, so it seems quite probable that they are actually iridis. The larvae of the two species are very similar. "-Oct 22, 2010.

notes:
DAE`09-3

Dave Etnier: " I relooked at the 7 Agapetus jocassee you bar-coded. The two in UT 1.1148, 10SMRTR1-035 and -036, both males, are jocassee, as are the three males from UT 1.1147 (-030, -031, -032); both -033 and -034 are larvae, and they could certainly be larvae of A. iridis. We have one lot of iridis from near there, same county, and the suggestion is that iridis emerges later than jocassee. We have taken the two species together, so it seems quite probable that they are actually iridis. The larvae of the two species are very similar. "-Oct 22, 2010.
